Calling `Timer.start()` after loosing focus, does not resume previously stopped task. 
To reproduce execute the example below and follow the following steps:
After the application launches, the log message ("Bug: foo") should appears every second. 
1. Press the "P" key to pause the logging task thus stopping the message from appearing. 
2. Make game window loose focus (e.g., by focusing on different window). 
3. Focus back on game window.
4. Press the "R" key to resume the stopped task.
Expected result:
The task should be resumed and the message should appear every second.
Actual result:
The task is not resumed. The message does not appear.

Tested on OS X Yosemite, with latest libgdx (1.6.1).

``` java
package com.badlogic.drop.desktop;

import com.badlogic.gdx.Game;
import com.badlogic.gdx.Gdx;
import com.badlogic.gdx.ScreenAdapter;
import com.badlogic.gdx.Input.Keys;
import com.badlogic.gdx.backends.lwjgl.LwjglApplication;
import com.badlogic.gdx.backends.lwjgl.LwjglApplicationConfiguration;
import com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Timer;
import com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Timer.Task;

public class DesktopLauncher {
    public static class BugReproduce extends Game{

        @Override
        public void create() {
            Timer.schedule(new Task() {

                @Override
                public void run() {
                    Gdx.app.log("Bug", "foo");
                }
            }, 1, 1);
            setScreen(new ScreenAdapter()); 
        }
        @Override
        public void render() {
            super.render();        
            if (Gdx.input.isKeyPressed(Keys.P)){
                Timer.instance().stop();
            }
            if (Gdx.input.isKeyPressed(Keys.R)){
                Timer.instance().start();
            }
        }
    }
    public static void main (String[] arg) {
        LwjglApplicationConfiguration config = new LwjglApplicationConfiguration();
        config.title = "BugReproduce";
        new LwjglApplication(new BugReproduce(), config);
    }
}
```

When a Label has the ellipsis set to true, and computePrefSize() is called but layout() is not, the GlyphLayout is left in an inconsistent state, because computePrefSize() updates the cache without considering the ellipsis to calculate the pref height.

So this is not usually problem, because the chances of calling computePrefSize without calling layout after are low. However, it is still possible and I encountered it developing my app. This is how the problem can be reproduced:

``` java
public class Test implements ApplicationListener {

    private Stage stage;
    private Container<Label> container;
    private Label label;

    @Override
    public void create() {
        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(1.0f, 1.0f, 1.0f, 1.0f);
        stage = new Stage();
        LabelStyle style = new LabelStyle();
        style.font = new BitmapFont();
        style.fontColor = Color.BLACK;
        label = new Label("", style);
        label.setEllipsis(true);
        container = new Container<Label>(label);
        container.setPosition(50.0f, 40.0f);
        container.size(50.0f);
        stage.addActor(container);
    }

    @Override
    public void resize(int width, int height) {
        stage.getViewport().update(width, height, true);
    }

    @Override
    public void render() {
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
        stage.act();
        stage.draw();
        label.setText("Very long text long text long text long text");
        stage.draw();

        label.getPrefHeight();
        label.getStyle().fontColor = Color.BLUE;

        stage.draw();
    }

    @Override
    public void pause() {

    }

    @Override
    public void resume() {

    }

    @Override
    public void dispose() {

    }

}
```

I propose as solution using a static tempLayout to calculate the preferred size, so the layout owned by the label is always kept consistent.
